"# Chapter 16 — Composing games

Fifteen chapters of widgets. Now a full game — small, complete, worked end to end. Sprite. Sound. Tile-map. Publish. Friend plays. Every step uses verbs from the previous chapters. The composer file is a single `.slat`.

## 16.1 The game

A tiny platformer. A hero sprite. Four tiles for the ground. One song. One HTTP publish so a friend on the same wifi can open a link and play.

## 16.2 The composer canvas

The whole cart is one canvas of nested canvases. Each nested canvas groups related widgets.

```scheme
(composer/canvas (list :bind '(cart/game))

  ;; ── metadata ────────────────────────────────
  (composer/canvas (list :bind '(cart/game :meta))
    (composer/text-field :bind '(cart/game :meta :title)
                         :label \"title\" :value \"tiny-platformer\")
    (composer/text-field :bind '(cart/game :meta :author)
                         :label \"author\" :value \"\"))

  ;; ── sprites ─────────────────────────────────
  (composer/canvas (list :bind '(cart/game :sprites))
    (composer/sprite-grid :bind '(cart/game :sprites :hero)
                          :size '(16 . 16) :palette 'html-16)
    (composer/sprite-grid :bind '(cart/game :sprites :grass)
                          :size '(8 . 8) :palette 'html-16)
    (composer/color-picker :bind '(cart/game :sprites :ink) :palette 'html-16))

  ;; ── tile map ────────────────────────────────
  (composer/canvas (list :bind '(cart/game :level))
    (composer/tile-map :bind '(cart/game :level :map)
                       :size '(24 . 8)
                       :tileset '(cart/game :sprites)))

  ;; ── animation ───────────────────────────────
  (composer/canvas (list :bind '(cart/game :anim))
    (composer/timeline :bind '(cart/game :anim :hero-walk)
                       :entities '(hero)
                       :duration 4 :fps 8))

  ;; ── sound ───────────────────────────────────
  (composer/canvas (list :bind '(cart/game :sound))
    (composer/instrument-picker :bind '(cart/game :sound :wave)
                                :choices '(sine square triangle saw noise))
    (composer/adsr :bind '(cart/game :sound :env))
    (composer/fx-chain :bind '(cart/game :sound :fx)
                       :available '(fx/reverb fx/delay fx/filter)))

  ;; ── music ───────────────────────────────────
  (composer/canvas (list :bind '(cart/game :music))
    (composer/slider :label \"BPM\" :bind '(cart/game :music :bpm)
                     :min 60 :max 240 :step 1 :value 120)
    (composer/piano-roll :bind '(cart/game :music :notes)
                         :range '(C3 . C6) :steps 32 :emit-shape 'sequence))

  ;; ── voices ──────────────────────────────────
  (composer/voice-pool :bind '(cart/game :pool) :steal 'oldest)

  ;; ── controls ────────────────────────────────
  (composer/button :label \"Play\"    :emits '(game/start))
  (composer/button :label \"Stop\"    :emits '(game/stop))
  (composer/button :label \"Publish\" :emits '(cart/publish))

  ;; ── live-code round-trip window ─────────────
  (composer/live-code :bind '(cart/game)))
```

Every widget from Chapters 3 through 12 is used here. The canvas is deeply nested — six inner canvases plus a voice-pool, four buttons, and a live-code widget. The whole thing is one Scheme value.

## 16.3 What the emit looks like

`composer/emit` on this canvas produces one giant `(composer/canvas ...)` form with all the inner canvases and widgets nested inside it, each with current state baked in. The form is a few hundred lines of Scheme. Save it to disk; you have a complete authoring surface as one file.

I verified the top-level structure with `bin/motoi eval` — the composer accepts the nested canvases, walks them, produces the expected canvas record with all children. The full emit is large but shape-wise it is exactly the pattern from previous chapters: canvas contains children, children contain more canvases, all bound paths write to specific slots in the target `cart/game` form.

## 16.4 The target form

The widgets write to a target `cart/game` form. In your cart file this looks like:

```
(define cart/game
  (:meta    (:title \"tiny-platformer\" :author \"\")
   :sprites (:hero (sprite/from-grid '((0 0 ...) ...))
             :grass (sprite/from-grid '((3 3 ...) ...))
             :ink 'crimson)
   :level   (:map (tile-map :size (24 . 8)
                            :cells ((0 6 1) (1 6 1) ...)))
   :anim    (:hero-walk (animation :entity 'hero
                                    :frames ((0 . hero-1) ...)))
   :sound   (:wave 'square
             :env (adsr :a 0.02 :d 0.1 :s 0.7 :r 0.2)
             :fx (fx-chain (fx/reverb :room 0.3 :wet 0.2)))
   :music   (:bpm 120
             :notes (sequence (note :pitch 'C4 :vel 0.8 :at 0 :dur 2) ...))
   :pool    (voice-pool :steal 'oldest :mix (1 2 3))))
```

Every slot filled with data the widgets composed. Every slot readable, editable, hand-writable.

## 16.5 Playing the game

Once the target form is populated, the runtime consumes it:

```scheme
(define (game/start)
  (song/play (cart/game :music :notes) :bpm (cart/game :music :bpm))
  (spawn-hero)
  (render-level (cart/game :level :map))
  (loop-frame))
```

The `game/start` function reads from the target and starts the play loop. The composer widgets have no runtime responsibility beyond writing the data; the runtime picks it up.

## 16.6 Publishing

```scheme
(define (cart/publish)
  (define s (http/serve :port 8080 :cart-dir \"carts\" :compose-perm 'local-only))
  (http/wait-until-ready s 2000)
  (display \"cart available at http://localhost:8080/play/tiny-platformer\")
  (newline)
  s)
```

Click the Publish button. The `cart/publish` function starts an HTTP server. Print the URL. Copy it. Text it to a friend. Friend opens the link. Friend plays the cart.

The compose route stays local-only. Friend cannot edit — they can only play. That is the sharing model: play is public, compose is private.

## 16.7 The live-code round-trip in action

The live-code widget at the bottom of the canvas shows the full emitted form as an editable panel. Every widget-driven edit updates the live-code. Every live-code edit updates the widgets.

Kid clicks a piano-roll cell to add a note. Live-code panel shows a new `(note :pitch 'C4 :vel 0.8 :at 0 :dur 1)` in the sequence. Kid changes `0.8` to `0.5` in the live-code panel. Piano-roll cell dims to reflect lower velocity.

Kid drags a slider to change BPM from 120 to 140. Live-code panel updates `:bpm 140`. Kid types `:bpm 100` back into the live-code panel. Slider knob moves to 100.

Round-trip visible. Round-trip editable from either side.

## 16.8 Saving the cart

```scheme
(composer/save game-canvas \"carts/tiny-platformer.slat\")
```

Writes the full canvas declaration to disk. Kids doing this from Curator see a save toast. From the REPL, the return value is the file path.

Reload:

```scheme
(define game-canvas-2 (composer/load \"carts/tiny-platformer.slat\"))
```

Reconstructs the canvas with all six inner canvases, all widgets, all bindings. Emit `game-canvas-2` and it matches the emit of `game-canvas`.

## 16.9 The kid on the plane test

A kid on a plane with no wifi opens Motoi. Opens `carts/tiny-platformer.slat`. Composer loads the file. Every widget renders on whatever surface is available — TUI on a laptop terminal, Curator canvas if graphical. Kid edits sprites. Kid tweaks the melody. Kid saves.

Plane lands. Kid opens wifi. Kid clicks Publish. Cart is now on `http://localhost:8080/play/tiny-platformer`. Kid uses a QR code app to make a QR code of the URL. Kid shows the code to a friend at school. Friend scans, opens the URL, plays.

Every step used composer verbs from Chapters 3 through 15. No cloud service. No account. No paid tier. The composer is just a pile of verbs; the kid arranged them into a game.

## 16.10 What the file looks like on disk

The saved cart is a Scheme file with two conceptual sections:

1. Top-level `(define ...)` forms for each target (`cart/game`, `hero-sprite`, `theme-song`, etc.).
2. A trailing `(composer/canvas ...)` declaration documenting the widgets.

Both parts are Scheme. Both parts survive hand-editing. Both parts round-trip.

Version-control it. Diff between two saves shows exactly which cells of a sprite changed, which notes moved in the piano-roll, which slider values shifted. `git blame` on a `.slat` file works.

## 16.11 Sharing without the server

If the kid does not want to run their own server, they can share the raw `.slat` file. A friend with Motoi installed opens it with `bin/motoi run tiny-platformer.slat`. Same cart. Same game.

The HTTP server is a convenience for browser-based play; the file is the artifact.

## 16.12 The whole book in one paragraph

Widgets are Scheme records. Canvases group widgets. Bindings connect widgets to target-form slots. Emit produces a form. Apply updates widgets from a form. Save writes to disk. Load reconstructs from disk. Sixteen chapters of variations on this theme. One game, worked end to end, using all of it.

## 16.13 What to remember from this chapter

- A full game cart uses widgets from every chapter, nested in canvases by concern (meta, sprites, level, sound, music, controls).
- The emit is a single `(composer/canvas ...)` form containing the whole widget graph.
- The target forms (sprite data, note sequences, tile cells) live in top-level defines the runtime consumes.
- Publish with `http/serve`; friend plays over HTTP.
- Save and load work over the whole nested canvas.
- Round-trip closes over disk, over surfaces, over composition depth.
- The composer is just a pile of verbs, deterministically arranged into a game by a kid.

The next section — Appendices A through H — provides reference material: every verb documented, every widget's ASCII mockup, every emit-shape, round-trip proofs, palette catalog, voice mixing recipes, TUI cheat-sheet, and the HTTP security guide.

## 16.14 Composing constraints — the multi-rule pattern

The tiny-platformer above is a game with many parts. Under it lives a smaller compositional skill: how to hold TWO game rules at once and pick the right verbs for each. This is the skill that separates 'my sprite moves' from 'my sprite moves until it hits the wall and then stops.'

### The pattern in four steps

When a prompt gives you two constraints — 'move right AND stop at the edge,' 'spawn a coin AND despawn it when collected,' 'animate a bounce AND halt when velocity is small' — walk through this shape:

1. **Name each constraint.** Write the two rules out in plain English before you type any code. 'Move right' is one rule. 'Stop when x is past 300' is another. If you can't articulate both rules in one sentence each, the prompt hasn't been read carefully enough.

2. **Pick the verb for each constraint.** One verb per constraint when possible. For 'move right,' the verb is `entity/set-vel! p 2 0`. For 'stop at edge,' the check is `(>= (entity/x p) right-edge)` followed by `(entity/set-vel! p 0 0)`. Prefer the smallest verb that names the rule.

3. **Compose in `on-frame`.** The frame loop is where both rules are checked every tick. Constraint 1 sets velocity if it should be moving. Constraint 2 zeroes velocity if the stop-condition holds. Both are re-evaluated 60 times a second.

4. **Verify each constraint independently.** Comment out the stop check; confirm the sprite moves. Uncomment the stop check, set initial velocity to zero; confirm the sprite doesn't move. If each rule works alone, the composition works.

### A worked example — move+stop

Prompt: 'Make a sprite move right and stop at the edge.'

Two constraints named:
- Constraint 1: move right (velocity +2 on x-axis).
- Constraint 2: stop when x >= 300.

Verbs picked:
- `entity/set-vel!` for both (setting non-zero for constraint 1, zero for constraint 2).
- `entity/x` and `>=` for the stop check.

Composed:

```scheme
(define (move-then-stop)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 20 120)))
    (entity/shape! p 'rect 12 12)
    (entity/set-vel! p 2 0)                    ; constraint 1: set initial velocity
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (world/step)
       (when (>= (entity/x p) 300)             ; constraint 2: check stop condition
         (entity/set-vel! p 0 0))
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 12 12)))))
(big-bang move-then-stop)
```

Every frame: step the world (which moves the sprite by its velocity). Then check if we've reached the edge. If yes, zero the velocity. Nothing else. Two rules; two lines that enforce them; the rest is boilerplate.

## 16.15 Drift detection — when your code stops matching the prompt

**Drift** is what happens when your code starts using verbs you didn't intend. You wrote 'move right and stop at the edge.' Your code uses `ai/wander` because you saw it in the reference and it seemed related. Your sprite wanders. It never stops at the edge because you never wrote a stop-check. The code compiled. The code ran. The code does not match the prompt.

Drift is the single most common failure mode when composing multi-constraint games with an LLM. The model has strong single-verb recall — it knows `entity/set-vel!`, it knows `ai/wander`, it knows `motion/move-to`. When two constraints have to be held together, the model sometimes picks a verb that's close-but-wrong for one of them, and the second constraint quietly gets dropped.

### The detection signal

You've drifted when any of these are true:

- Your code uses a verb that wasn't named or implied by the prompt.
- One of the constraints in the prompt has no corresponding verb call in your code.
- The behavior when you run it doesn't match what the prompt described.
- You've written more than 30 lines and the prompt asked for something simple.

### The recovery move

When you detect drift:

1. **Stop.** Don't try to patch. Don't add more verbs to compensate.
2. **Re-read the prompt.** Word for word. Underline each constraint.
3. **Restart.** Not from scratch, but from a clean minimum: `(world/reset!)`, one entity, one verb per constraint, on-frame that composes them. Build up from that.

Restarting is not a defeat. It is the correct move when your code has drifted from the prompt's intent. Every experienced programmer restarts constantly. The five-minute restart beats the fifty-minute patch.

### An example of drift and recovery

Bad response to 'make a sprite move right and stop at the edge':

```scheme
(define (drifted-version)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 20 120)))
    (entity/shape! p 'rect 12 12)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (ai/wander p)                    ; DRIFT — wander is not 'move right'
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 12 12)))))
```

Symptoms: The sprite meanders. Never stops at any edge. The prompt said 'move right' — clearly directional — but the code uses `ai/wander`, which is random motion. Constraint 1 has drifted (wrong verb). Constraint 2 has vanished (no stop-check at all).

Recovery: apply the four-step pattern above. Two constraints. `entity/set-vel!` for move right. `entity/x` compared to edge for stop. Compose in on-frame. Verify each. Result: the correct code from §16.14.

Total time to recover: about two minutes if you catch the drift when the sprite starts wandering. Two hours if you try to add more verbs to fix the wandering and end up with `ai/wander` layered under `ai/steer` layered under `entity/limit-x`. Restart is cheaper.

## 16.16 Prompt-fidelity as a first-class skill

Reading the prompt is a skill. Holding the prompt in mind while writing code is a skill. Noticing when your code has drifted is a skill. All three are learnable, and all three matter more than knowing every verb.

When a prompt has two constraints, the code should have two constraint-enforcing calls. When a prompt has three constraints, three calls. When the prompt-to-call ratio starts to slip — five prompt constraints, ten calls, six of them not corresponding to any prompt phrase — something has drifted. Stop. Re-read. Restart.

This is not about writing shorter code. Shorter code that ignores the prompt is worse than longer code that matches it. This is about writing code whose SHAPE matches the prompt's shape. Each constraint gets its representative. Nothing extra. Nothing missing.

See book-of-arcade-games appendix-L for six worked micro-games that follow this exact multi-constraint pattern, and book-of-scheme appendix-D for the 'move-until-condition' pattern entry.
")
